Since the N pole of the compass is the direction of the current, when the direction of the current is changed, the direction of the needle moves in reverse.

If the direction of the current is reversed, the direction indicated by the N pole of the compass is reversed. This means that the magnetic field is formed counterclockwise with respect to the direction of the current flowing through the conductor, and the N pole points to the direction of the tangent of the magnetic field. When the direction of the current changes, the direction of the magnetic field is reversed, so the direction indicated by the N pole of the compass is also reversed.
